[[File:Qinshihuang.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Qin Shi Huangdi]], the first Chinese emperor, ordered a [[burning of books and burying of scholars|great destruction of books]] for fear of the Confucian ideas that they contained.]]
'''Bibliophobia''' is the fear or hatred of books.<ref>{{citation |title=Oxford English Dictionary |url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/18647 |year=2014}}</ref> Such fear often arises from fear of the effect books can have on society or culture.<ref name=Holbrook>{{citation |title=The Fear of Books |first=Holbrook |last=Jackson |authorlink=Holbrook Jackson |publisher=University of Illinois Press |year=1932 |isbn=9780252070402}}</ref>{{rp|2}} Bibliophobia is a common cause of [[censorship]] and [[book burning]].

In his 1999 Matthews lecture at [[Birkbeck College]], [[Tom Shippey]] discussed bibliophobia in the [[Middle Ages]].  This arose when the literate professions, such as the clergy and [[beadle]]s, would exploit and terrify the [[illiterate]] masses by their command of texts such as religious and legal documents.  He illustrated this with examples from Anglo-Saxon literature such as ''[[The Pardoner's Tale]]''.<ref name=TS>{{citation |title=Bibliophobia: hatred of the book in the Middle Ages |first=Tom |last=Shippey |authorlink=Tom Shippey |publisher=Birkbeck College |year=2001}}</ref>

