{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Henri Matisse, 1902, Notre-Dame, une fin d'après-midi, oil on paper mounted on canvas, 72.4 x 54.6 cm, Albright-Knox Art Gallery.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=230px | title=Notre-Dame, une fin d'après-midi | artist=[[Henri Matisse]] | year=1902 | type=[[oil painting|Oil on paper mounted on canvas]] | height_metric=72.5 | width_metric=54.5 | height_imperial={{frac|28|1|2}} | width_imperial={{frac|21|1|2}} | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] | museum=[[Albright–Knox Art Gallery]] }} '''''Notre-Dame, une fin d'après-midi''''' ("A Glimpse of Notre-Dame in the Late Afternoon") is a painting by [[Henri Matisse]] from 1902. Its somber coloration is typical of Matisse's works executed between the end of 1901 and the end of 1903, a period of personal difficulties for the artist. This episode has been called Matisse's Dark Period.<ref name="Spurling33">Spurling, p. 33</ref>
The work is an oil painting on paper mounted on canvas and it measures 72.5 × 54.5&nbsp;cm (28½ × 21½ in). It is in the [[Albright–Knox Art Gallery]], [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]].
==Background== Between 1896 and 1901, Matisse's painting had progressed from the subdued tones of his earliest works to an intense colorism that prefigured the [[Fauvism]] to come. In 1896 and 1897 he had traveled to [[Brittany]], where the Australian painter [[John Peter Russell]] encouraged him to paint ''[[en plein air]]''. Through Russell he met [[Camille Pissarro]], whose influence was decisive in making a colorist of Matisse.<ref>UCLA Art Council 1966, pp. 9–10.</ref> In 1898 he traveled to [[London]], where he studied the works of [[J. M. W. Turner]]; then, after a year spent in [[Corsica]] and [[Toulouse]], he returned to Paris, where the startling boldness of his work was admired by other young artists.<ref name="UCLA10">UCLA Art Council 1966, p. 10</ref> His paintings found few buyers, however, and his wife, Amélie, had to open a dress shop to support their household.<ref name="UCLA10"/>
In May 1902 a major financial scandal, the [[Thérèse Humbert|Humbert Affair]], unexpectedly ensnared Amélie's family. Her mother ( who was the Humbert family's housekeeper) and father became scapegoats in the scandal; as a result, Matisse was forced to spend much of his time during the next year dealing with lawyers and journalists.<ref name="Spurling33" /> His studio was searched by detectives, and his wife's family was menaced by angry mobs of fraud victims.<ref name="Spurling33" /> According to art historian [[Hilary Spurling]], "their public exposure, followed by the arrest of his father-in-law, left Matisse as the sole breadwinner for an extended family of seven. This is why he switched to painting canvases that were at least potentially saleable".<ref name="Spurling33" />
Inspired by [[Auguste Rodin|Rodin]] and [[Antoine-Louis Barye|Barye]], Matisse struggled to master volume in sculpture as well as in painting. He darkened his palette, with the results seen in the present work, and in such paintings as ''Carmelina'' (1903, in the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]).<ref name="UCLA10" />
